      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In his review of Stefan Kanfer's biography, ''Groucho'' (June 18), Gary Giddins notes that Julius Marx, ''who was acerbic and hid his money in a grouch bag, became Groucho.''</p>
        <p>How many readers know about grouch bags? They were small pouches, often worn beneath the clothing of traveling performers to conceal their emergency money or valuables. Circus people, vaudevillians and other intemperate spenders were considered ill tempered or grouchy, and their moneybags were called grouch bags.</p>
        <p>Richard Weiner  New York</p>
      </block>
